title: Central Park beginner Runners
description:
*note: please rsvp as ‚Äúgoing‚Äù only if you are actually going to allow others to come as the max slot is set to 20! Thanks!

Running can be overwhelming and a bit daunting if you are just starting out. That‚Äôs why we‚Äôve created the Central Park Beginner Runners Club, a relaxed, no pressure group for anyone looking to ease into running, enjoy the outdoors, and meet friendly faces along the way. Whether you‚Äôve never run a mile or are just getting back into it, we‚Äôll take it slow together with an easy 3 mile jog on Sunday mornings.

If you need to take a breather and walk, please feel free to let me know and we can slow down. All i ask is that you try your best! However, there is no pressure as this is a beginner friendly group!

If you're interested in running together, feel free to join us anytime! We'll gather every Sunday morning at the Gapstow bridge. You can expect the pace to be anywhere between 10-13min mile pace.

Our usual route will start from the Gapstow bridge then we will run up north to the reservoir and do a lap around. That should be about 3 miles. Depending on how people feel, we may jog back to the original meetup spot or we can walk back. üôÉ

We'll meet at 10:00 AM and aim to finish by 11:00 AM at the latest. Please bring the bare minimum as it may be difficult to find a place to store your stuff!

Whether you're a beginner runner, looking to lose weight, or just want to run, everyone is welcome!

title: Weeknight kayak polo @ Pier 66
description:
Please RSVP several days in advance, and check back here (and/or on Slack) before you come to make sure the session has not been cancelled. Summer storms can be hard to predict, and sometimes we need to cancel at the last minute.

Our weeknight kayak polo sessions at Pier 66 typically consist of some warm-up, and some combination of basic skills drills & practice, and and informal scrimmages. The Pier 66 location, as well as the tides, currents, and waves on the river, result in conditions that can be quite challenging for beginners, so please check with the session host(s) before signing up if you are new to kayak polo and advanced kayaking (e.g., whitewater or open-water sea kayaking).

We have club gear available (boats, paddles, PFDs, sprayskirts, helmets). You should bring water/paddling shoes, clothes that can get wet (no cotton) and a change for afterwards, and a towel & soap if you want to shower. Membership covers unlimited sessions during the season, or you can pay $25 per session. Your first session with our club is free, however. More info can be found at https://www.nykayakpolo.org/membership/.

title: Empire Skate Clubs 2025 Sleepy Hollow Halloween Skate
description:
**HIGHLIGHTS:**
We group up from 8:45 a.m. to 9:15 a.m.
WE SKATE OFF AT 9:15 A.M. !!
This is an INTERMEDIATE to ADVANCED LEVEL SKATE EVENT of approximately 30 miles from the Lincoln Center area in Manhattan to Sleepy Hollow in Westchester County, NY (This event description will be followed by another with options to meet us along the route in upper Manhattan or the Bronx if you prefer fewer miles or a later start time.)

Much of the route will be on trails including the Hudson River Greenway and the South County Trail which we can now access from the newly-paved trail in Van Cortlandt Park in the Bronx.
We are hoping to have a sag wagon. For many years, RON and JAN have been kind enough to volunteer their cars and time to make the journey more comfortable for their skater friends. We will let you know if there will be a sag wagon for bags and costume parts etc. in a future post.
The Tarrytown Parade Committee has invited us back to roll in the parade as we did in 2017, 2019, 2022, 2023 and 2024. Both Tarrytown and Sleepy Hollow go all out with decorations and create a very festive atmosphere for their visitors and those who participate in and attend the parade.
**THE SKATE:**

Join MOONMAN PETE as he leads a group of costumed skaters north from Manhattan to the Old Dutch Church and the Sleepy Hollow Cemetery in Sleepy Hollow, NY to chase down the Headless Horseman, the fictional character from Washington Irving's Classic story, "The Legend of Sleepy Hollow". The remains of author Washington Irving lie in the cemetery and, according to legend, so do the remains the Headless Hessian Horseman, who apparently rises up each evening and gallops through the village in search of the head that he lost in battle.
In recent years, the skate has started out on the trails of Riverside Park and the Hudson River Greenway and continued through Inwood in upper Manhattan until we cross over to the Bronx via the Broadway Bridge. After a few miles in the Bronx, we return to the trails as we enter Westchester County‚Äôs South County Trail and follow it all the way to Dobbs Ferry, NY. At that point, we skate west to the Hudson River and roll north through several river villages until we reach our destination ‚Äì the Old Dutch Church and the Sleepy Hollow Cemetery.
Traditionally, we gather for a meal after the skate, but you can choose to explore the villages instead. The Metro-North train from Tarrytown to Manhattan is nearby and provides an express trip to Grand Central of approximately 50 to 60 minutes.
More details about the event, including meet-up options, the route, and the post-skate gathering will follow shortly in the "Discussion" section of the event post.
HALLOWEEN ON WHEELS is 3 weeks away‚Ä¶.get busy with the costume creation, get yourself fit for the skate and the parade, and join the Empire Skate Club as it celebrates one of the year's best holidays on skates!

title: Monday Speed Workout - McCarren Track
description:
Monday Speed Workout at the Mccarren Track!! The best way to start your week!

tl;dr- Fire up your week with a speed workout for runners of all paces and abilities. We're excited and we hope you are too!!

***

All The Details:
There's only one trick to getting faster... and that is to run fast!

Come join TMIRCE in Williamsburg @ the McCarren Track for a free, creative speed workout guaranteed to make you faster one step at a time.

Lace up, show up! All paces welcome! You are not too slow! And yes, we run in the rain!

Workouts will consist of short intervals (usually a combo of 200m to 1200m) with rest periods in between. We total \~3 miles. It's a new workout every week!

Afterwards we'll head over to a local bar for some post-run refreshments.

***

On Attendance:

* It's informal running so RSVPs are optional. We tend to get a lot more runners than RSVPs.
* There is NO secure place to store bags, valuables, etc. Please use caution and do not bring anything you cannot afford to lose. We pile our stuff together and are (relatively) nearby for the duration of the workout but no promises. We have never had a problem with theft, but that doesn't mean it can't happen.

***

The Fine Print:
If you have any symptoms of COVID-19, believe you may have been exposed to someone with the virus, or satisfy any other condition that would put yourself or others at risk of COVID-19 transmission please stay home.

We expect everyone who shows up to adhere to our guidelines and the policies put forth by our health and local government officials. However, even with the best of intentions it‚Äôs possible that someone could contract or pass along COVID-19. TMIRCE, its members and run leaders assume no responsibility for the health and safety of any attendee. In accordance, each attendee agrees to assume personal responsibility for any injury or illness (COVID-19 related or otherwise) that may occur during or after participation in a TMIRCE event.
